ination of logical operations to create a priority score.\n\nWait, perhaps function 5 can use a logical operation to prioritize bins that are larger than the item.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    larger = bins >= item\n    return np.tanh(np.pi * item / bins) * larger + np.log(bins + 1e-8) * (1 - larger)\n\nBut this would give higher priority to larger bins that can fit the item.\n\nHmm, that's a good approach. Each function should ideally return higher values for suitable bins.\n\nFunction 6: Use tan and log.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.tan(np.pi * item / bins) * np.exp(item - np.mean(bins)) + np.log(bins + 1e-8)\n\nWait, but this is similar to example 2, which uses tan and tanh. Maybe I can modify it differently.\n\nFunction 6:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.tan(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.exp(item - np.max(bins)) + np.log2(bins + 1e-8)\n\nFunction 7: Use absolute differences and hyperbolic functions.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    diff = np.abs(bins - item)\n    return np.tanh(diff) * np.exp(item - np.mean(bins)) + np.log(bins + 1e-8)\n\nFunction 8: Use matrix operations like element-wise multiplication.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.tanh(np.dot(bins, np.ones_like(item))) * np.exp(item - np.mean(bins)) + np.log(bins + 1e-8)\n\nWait, but np.dot here might not be the right approach. Perhaps use element-wise multiplication instead.\n\nFunction 8:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.tanh(item * bins) * np.exp(item - np.mean(bins)) + np.log(bins + 1e-8)\n", 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log10(item + 1) * (item * np.max(bins)) + np.tanh(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sqrt(item)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.std(bins)) * np.exp(