ority = (bins - item) * (1 - (item / bins)).\n\nBut for bins < item, it's 0.\n\nSo, function:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    fit = np.maximum(0, bins - item)\n    used = np.maximum(0, 1 - (item / (bins + 1e-9)))\n    return fit * used\n\nBut I'm not sure if that's necessary. Maybe it's better to just use (bins - item) * (item / bins) for bins >= item.\n\nBut let's proceed.\n\nFunction 2: Worst Fit. Here, the priority is higher for bins with larger remaining space that can fit the item.\n\nSo, priority is (bins - item) for bins >= item, else 0. But to make it worst fit, we prioritize the largest remaining space.\n\nBut that's similar to function 1. Maybe function 2 could be:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.maximum(0, bins - item) * np.log(bins + 1e-9)\n", 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.log(item + 1) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.std(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(-item + bins) * np.mean(bins) + np.log(item + 1) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - np.mean(bins)) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.log(item + 1)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - np.mean(bins)) * np.log(item + 1) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - np.mean(bins)) * np.log(item + 1) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.log(item + 1)\n', 'def priority(item: