* np.log(bins + 1) + np.tanh(item - np.mean(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.log(item + bins) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * 2\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.max(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.min(bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    # Only consider bins where the item can fit\n    remaining[remaining < 0] = np.inf\n    # The priority is the remaining space, with higher priority to bins where the item fits and leaves the least space\n    return remaining\n\nThis function gives higher priority to bins where the item can fit and leaves the least remaining space.\n\n### Another example:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    # Calculate the remaining space for each bin\n    remaining = bins - item\n    # For bins that can\'t fit the item, set priority to 0\n    remaining[remaining < 0] = 0\n    # Calculate the utilization of each bin\n    utilization = bins / (bins + item)\n    # Combine remaining space and utilization with equal weights\n    return remaining + utilization\n\nThis function prioritizes bins that have more remaining space and higher utilization.\n\n### Task:\n\nGenerate 10 such unique functions, each using a unique combination of allowed operations.\n\n### Deliverables:\n\n1. Provide 10 unique Python functions, each named `priority`, with the exact signature.\n\nEach function must be a correct implementation, but the actual "correctness" is determined by the heuristic for the bin packing problem. So the functions can vary in their approach, as long as they are valid heuristics.\n\n### Final Notes:\n\n- The functions must be vectorized and use only numpy operations.\n- All functions must return an array of the same size as bins.\n\n### \n\n### Additional Constraints:\n\n- The item can be any float, positive or negative.\n- The bins array can have a size from 1 to 1000.\n</think>\n\n### Implementation 1:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    remaining[remaining < 0] = np.inf\n    return remaining\n\n### Implementation 2:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    remaining[remaining < 0] = 0\n    utilization = bins / (bins + item)\n    return remaining + utilization\n\n### Implementation 3:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    remaining[remaining < 0] = np.inf\n    return np.exp(remaining) + np.log(item + bins)\n\n### Implementation 4:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    remaining[remaining < 0] = np.inf\n    return (remaining * np.max(bins)) + (item * np.min(bins))\n\n### Implementation 5:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    remaining[remaining < 0] = np.inf\n    return (remaining * np.mean(bins)) + (item * np.std(bins))\n\n### Implementation 6:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    remaining[remaining < 0] = np.inf\n    return (remaining * np.sum(bins)) + (item * np.prod(bins))\n\n### Implementation 7:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    remaining[remaining < 0] = np.inf\n    return (remaining * np.log(bins)) + (item * np.exp(bins))\n\n### Implementation 8:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    remaining[remaining < 0] = np.inf\n    return (remaining * np.sin(bins)) + (item * np.cos(bins))\n\n### Implementation 9:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    remaining[remaining < 0] = np.inf\n    return (remain