al functions and array operations I can use:\n\nMath functions: exp, log, sin, cos, tan, sqrt, abs, etc.\nArray operations: np.add, np.subtract, np.multiply, np.divide, np.power, np.exp, np.log, np.sin, np.std, etc.\nConstants: 1e-8, math.pi, math.e.\n\nI'll try to combine these in different ways, ensuring each function uses a unique combination.\n\nFunction 1:\nUse item multiplied by the standard deviation of bins, then add the natural log of (item + 1) multiplied by the sine of pi times (item / bins).\n\nFunction 2:\nMultiply item with the log of bins plus a small epsilon, then add the exponential of (item - bins).\n\nWait, but the examples already have similar structures. I need to make each function distinct.\n\nFunction 3:\nPerhaps use the square root of bins and combine it with exponential functions. For example, sqrt(bins) multiplied by exp(item) plus something else.\n\nWait, let me think of different operations. Maybe using cos instead of sin, or combining multiple functions.\n\nFunction 4:\nWhat if I use the ratio of item to bins, apply sqrt and exp, then add a log term.\n\nFunction 5:\nUse the difference between bins and item, apply exp and log.\n\nHmm, I need to ensure each function is unique in the combination of operations and functions used.\n\nLet me start drafting each function one by one, making sure each has a distinct formula.\n\nFunction 1:\nCombine item with the standard deviation of bins, multiplied by an exponential term, plus the log of (item +1) and sin.\n\nFunction 2:\nUse item multiplied by the log of (bins + epsilon), then add exp(item - bins).\n\nFunction 3:\nUse sqrt of (bins + epsilon) multiplied by exp(item) plus cos of (pi * item / bins).\n\nFunction 4:\nCompute the ratio of item to bins, apply exp and log, then add sin of that ratio.\n\nFunction 5:\nMultiply (item + epsilon) with the log of bins, then add exp of (item - bins).\n\nWait, I think I'm repeating similar structures. Let me vary more.\n\nFunction 6:\nUse the difference between bins and item, apply exp, then multiply with the log of (item + 1), plus cos of (pi * item / bins).\n\nFunction 7:\nTake the reciprocal of (bins + epsilon), multiply by exp(item), then add the log of (item + 1) multiplied by sin(pi * item / bins).\n\nFunction 8:\nUse the square of (item / bins), apply exp, then add the log of (item + 1) multiplied by cos(pi * item / bins).\n\nFunction 9:\nCompute the ratio of item to bins, apply sqrt, multiply by exp(item), then add sin(pi * ratio).\n\nFunction 10:\nUse the log of (bins + epsilon) multiplied by exp(item), then add the square root of (item / bins).\n\nWait, I think I can structure each function to have a unique combination of functions and operations, ensuring no two functions are the same.\n\nI'll proceed to write each function with these combinations, making sure each uses a different set of operations and functions.\n</think>\n\nHere are 10 unique implementations of the `priority` function, each using a distinct combination of allowed operations:\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.std(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.log(item + 1) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log(bins + 1e-8)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (np.sqrt(bins) * item) * np.exp(item) + np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    ratio = item / (bins + 1e-8)\n    return np.exp(ratio) * np.log(1 + ratio) + np.sin(np.pi * ratio)\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log(bins + 1e-8)) * np.exp(item) + np.log(item + 1) * np.cos(np.pi * (item / bins))\n```\n\n```python\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (np.exp(ite