bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.std(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))#\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.log(item + 1) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * 8\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.std(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))#\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.log(item + 1) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * 8\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - np.mean(bins)) * (np.log(item + 1) + np.sin(np.pi * item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.cos(item - bins) * (item * np.std(bins)) + np.log(item + 2) * np.sin(np.pi * item / bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.log(item + 1) * np.sin(np.pi * item / bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.std(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * item / bins) * 4\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log(item + 1) * (np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.log(item + 1) * np.sin(np.pi * item / bins) * 3\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.std(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * item / bins) * 6\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.cos(item - bins) * (item * np.mean(bins)) + np.log(item + 2) * np.sin(np.pi * item / bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.log(item + 1) * np.sin(np.pi * item / bins) * 5\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.log(item + bins) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.log(item + bins) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.log(item + bins) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.log(item + bins) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.log(item + bins) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.log(item + bins) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * 4\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log(bins + 1e-8)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sqrt(item) * np.mean(bins) + np.log(item + bins) * np.exp(item - bins)\n', "def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    # Your code here\n    pass\n\n### Loss Value:\nThe loss is the value of the function when bins are filled with item. \n\nBut for the purposes of this task, it's not necessary to compute the loss.\n\n### Testing:\nEach function will be tested in the code to ensure they produce a valid output.\n\n### Constraints:\n- The bins array is 1D.\n- The bins can have zero or more items already placed in them.\n- The bins can be of any size, but all have the same capacity.\n\n### Additional Notes:\n- You can use any allowed operations any number of times.\n- The functions can be more complex than the examples, but must be unique.\n\n### Example of Unique Function:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item) * np.mean(bins) + np.log(item) * np.max(bins) + np.sqrt(item) * np.min(bins)\n\n### How to make functions unique:\nEach function must combine operations in a unique way. For example, combining different operations and functions in a unique way.\n\n### Suggestion:\nTo ensure uniqueness, try to vary the combination of operations and the order in which they are applied.\n\n### Approach:\nThe functions are heuristics to determine which bin to place the item into. The priority is computed for each bin, and the item is placed into the bin with the highest priority.\n\n### Bin Packing Problem:\nIn the bin packing problem, the goal is to pack a set of items into the minimum number of bins possible without exceeding the bin's capacity. Heuristics are used to approximate the optimal solution.\n\n### Heuristic Functions:\nThe heuristic function assigns a priority score to each bin based on certain criteria, such as the bin's remaining capacity, the size of the item, and other factors.\n\n### Common Heuristics:\n- First Fit: Place the item in the first bin that can accommodate it.\n- Best Fit: Place the item in the bin where it fits best, minimizing the remaining space.\n- Worst Fit: Place the item in the bin that leaves the most space.\n- Random Fit: Place the item in a randomly selected bin that can accommodate it.\n\n### Heuristic Implementation:\nThe priority function is used in these heuristics to determine the best bin for the item.\n\n### Suggested Heuristic Functions:\n- Remaining Space: The priority is based on the remaining space in the bin.\n- Proportional: Priority is proportional to the remaining space.\n- Fit: The fit of the item into the bin.\n- Decreasing: Prioritize bins in a certain order.\n\n### Possible Function Combinations:\nUse combinations of the allowed operations to create unique priority functions.\n\n### Example Function:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log(bins + item) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.mean(bins) * np.sqrt(item)\n\n### Function Design:\nEach function should be a mathematical expression that combines the item size and the bin's characteristics to produce a priority score.\n\n### Design Considerations:\n- The function should be sensitive to the item's size and the bin's remaining capacity.\n- The function should encourage efficient packing, such as placing larger items in bins with more remaining space.\n- The function should avoid assigning the item to bins that are too small.\n\n### Function Testing:\nEach function should be tested to ensure it returns an array of the same size as bins.\n\n### Final Output:\nGenerate 10 unique functions following the above guidelines.\n\n### Summary:\nEach function must be unique in the way it combines the allowed operations to compute the priority score. The functions should be as simple as possible but each must be unique.\n\n### Additional Notes:\n- Use NumPy functions wherever possible for vectorized operations.\n- Avoid using loops if possible to ensure efficiency.\n</think>\n\n### Solution Code\n\n```python\nimport numpy as np\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item) * np.mean(bins) + np.log(item) * np.max(bins) + np.sqrt(item) * np.min(bins)\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log(bins + item) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.mean(bins) * np.sqrt(item)\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.log(bins + 1e-8) + np.exp(item) * np.mean(bins)\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.sqrt(item) * np.mean(bins) + np.log(item + bins) * np.exp(item - bins)\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log(item + bins) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.exp(item) * np.mean(bins)\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item) * (np.max(bins) - np.min(bins)) + np.log(item) * np.mean(bins)\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.sqrt(item) * np.mean(bins) + np.exp(item) * np.max(bins) + np.log(item) * np.min(bins)\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.log(bins + 1e-8) + np.sqrt(item) * np.mean(bins)\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item) * (np.max(bins) - np.min(bins)) + np.log(item) * np.mean(bins)\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log(item + bins) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.exp(item) * np.mean(bins)\n", 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.log(bins + 1e-8)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + (item * np.mean(bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.mean(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.log(item + bins) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * 2 + np.log(item + bins) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * 2 + np.log(item + bins) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * 2 + np.log(item + bins) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * 2 + np.log(item + bins) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * 2 + np.log(item + bins) * np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * 2\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * np.var(bins)) * np.exp(item - bins) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins))\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.max(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.min(bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - np.mean(bins)) * (item * np.max(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.min(bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.mean(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.min(bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - bins) * (item * np.mean(bins)) + np.sin(np.pi * (item / bins)) * np.min(bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(ite